FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - JAPAN (11): (MIYAZAKI) UPDATE, VACCINATION
*****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Wed 19 May 2010
Source: Kyodo News [edited]
<http://home.kyodo.co.jp/modules/fstStory/index.php?storyid=501636>


The farm ministry plans to slaughter all pigs and cows within a 10-km
[6.2-mi] radius of the areas hit by foot-and-mouth disease [FMD] in
Miyazaki Prefecture to contain the spread of the infection,
government sources said Wednesday [19 May 2010].

A total of 135 000 cows and pigs will be given vaccines before they
are slaughtered, the sources said. The Ministry of Agriculture,
Forestry and Fishers is set to make an announcement on the matter
later Wednesday [19 May 2010].

The areas subject to the slaughter involve 4 towns and surrounding
areas, including the town of Kawaminami. The government is making
arrangements to pay compensation to farmers worth 600 000 yen [approx
USD 6500] per cow and 40 000 [approx. USD 435] per pig, the sources said.

On Tuesday [18 May 2010], the farm ministry's expert panel on
tackling the FMD advised the government to consider using vaccines as
it has become quite difficult to prevent the spread just by
slaughtering livestock.

To contain the infection, the farm ministry has judged that it would
be necessary to slaughter healthy cows and pigs in the area where the
prefecture bans farmers from moving their livestock to prevent the
disease from spreading.

Vaccines can control the symptoms and delay the infection from
spreading but it does not completely prevent livestock from being
infected with the disease.

"It is important to take swift vigorous measures to prevent the
spread of the infection," Prime Minister Yukio Hatoyama told reporters.

Meanwhile, Hatoyama denied that the government or the prefectural
government is responsible for the spread of the disease.

--
