******
[2]
Date: Wed 19 May 2010
Source: The Mainichi Daily News [edited]
<http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/news/20100519p2a00m0na009000c.html>


The government on Wednesday [19 May 2010] decided to vaccinate and
slaughter all livestock within a 10-km [6.2-mi] radius of farms hit
by an outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease [FMD] in 4 Miyazaki Prefecture towns.

Officials made the decision after concluding that there was a need to
speedily control the spread of the disease to save time for the
slaughter of cattle.

The government will also consider providing compensation to farmers
outside the designated areas who have been affected by the outbreak.

According to the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries,
some 118 000 head of [pigs and cattle] known to have contracted the
disease or strongly suspected to have it were due to be slaughtered
as of Wednesday morning [19 May 2010], but so far only 60 000 have
been culled. In the meantime the highly contagious disease continues to spread.

To control the speed of infections, livestock within a 10-km radius
of affected farms in the 4 Miyazaki Prefecture towns of Tsuno,
Kawaminami, Takanabe, and Shintomi will be vaccinated [see map at
<http://fc-miyazaki.com/english/access/index.html>]. Eventually, all
of the animals will be slaughtered to prevent the disease from spreading.

It will be the 1st time for vaccines to be used in Japan as a measure
against FMD.

The government has enough vaccines for the O-type virus that is
currently circulating to cover 700 000 head of livestock. It is
expected that about 100 000 more cows and pigs within a 10-km radius
of the affected areas would be subject to vaccinations.

Use of a vaccine would not completely prevent infections, but if an
animal were infected, emission of the virus could be controlled to a
certain degree. Since the spread of infections would slow down, the
number of animals that would need to be slaughtered would decrease,
thus buying more time.

When questioned Monday [17 May 2010] over criticism from opposition
parties that Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries Minister Hirotaka
Akamatsu was slow in responding to the outbreak, Prime Minister Yukio
Hatoyama indicated that priority would be placed on controlling the
disease rather than pursuing officials' responsibility.

"What is important is to take strong, prompt measures to prevent the
spread of infections. This is something that comes before determining
where the responsibility lies," he said.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[A somewhat similar FMD control policy was applied in the Netherlands
in 2001, designated "vaccination to kill". However, from the
available information it seems that the initial aim of the
vaccination on affected premises in Japan is mainly to prevent
increased virus emission from the animals whose culling has been
delayed and further spread within the area already contaminated.

Further details on the vaccination programme are anticipated with
interest; a plausible plan will include early preventive vaccination
within an area around the zone declared as infected.

As of 18 May 2010, the total number of FMD outbreaks in Miyazaki has
reached 131, of which 118 in Kawaminami, 4 in Ebino, 4 in Takabane, 3
in Tsuno, and 2 in the most recently affected Shintomi. - Mod.AS]
